There are two main ways to use Notion with the Model Context Protocol (MCP). 

First, Notion provides an official remote MCP server accessed via OAuth [1][2]. This is recommended for interactive chat in web interfaces like Claude.ai or Cursor, as it requires human authorization but handles authentication seamlessly without manual token management [3][2].

Second, several community-maintained, open-source MCP servers allow for headless, automated, or token-based workflows using Notion Personal Access Tokens (PATs) [2][4]. These are suitable for agents, cron jobs, or CI/CD pipelines [2][4]. To configure these, add the server to your MCP client's configuration file [2][5]:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "notion": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "notion-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "NOTION_TOKEN": "ntn_your_token_here"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Consult the documentation for your chosen repository, such as those by awkoy or KokomiSensei, to select the best fit for your specific automation needs [2][4][6].
